concept.description: A type of asset that is exclusively used and governed by the business user community. Its instance assets, and all instances instantiating its subtypes, pertain to the business organization. Business assets typically include business concepts like Business Term, Business Process, Line of Business, etc. that help to build the semantics of any organization with insufficient details to build an actual business application.

A type of asset that represents details of organizational data in two layers. One layer is independent of any particular technology for non-technical stakeholder communication. The other one is taking the implementation system for technical stakeholder communication into account.

Examples: Data Element, Table

A type of asset that is used to monitor and advocates to maximize performance or utilization of other Business and Data assets while minimizing the risk factors in alignment with Organisational/Business goals.

A piece of information technology (hardware, software, database, software platform) that helps an organization to run a business application.

Examples: Database, File

attributeReference.value:
This is the main approval process for terms. 

The subject matter expert starts by reviewing the definition. 
After that the stakeholders are given an opportunity to provide comments on the given term. The subject matter expert is then given a task to process the comments and the stewards are asked to vote for term approval. The stakeholders are notified of the final outcome.

labelReference.description: The description of the asset. This is typically a more verbose way to describe what the asset means.

attributeReference.value:
This approval workflow is specifically designed to approve data assets. 

The subject matter expert is first asked to review the definition. After that, he can add related business terms and propose rules & policies to which the data asset should comply. 
After that the stakeholders are given an opportunity to provide comments. The subject matter expert is then provided with a task to process the comments and is asked to verify the provided rules & policies. 

Tghe next step is that all the stewards of the related policies & rules are asked to vote for compliance of their rule/policy. If all stewards vote yes, the stakeholders and the subject matter expert is notified and the process ends. If one of the stewards votes no, the subject matter expert is asked to adjust the data asset for compliance and the voting process is triggered again.

attributeReference.value:
This is a very basic approval process which can be used for different purposes.

The steward is asked to vote for approval. If approved, the term is marked as 'accepted' and the stakeholders are notified. If rejected, the user that initiated the workflow is notified of the rejection and the flow is ended.
